WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:36.436 --> 00:00:38.972
<i> LYNSEY: Pummeled
 with tank fire mortar rounds.</i>

00:00:40.306 --> 00:00:42.575
<i> Riots for bread.</i>

00:00:42.642 --> 00:00:44.377
<i> Women who tried
 to commit suicide</i>

00:00:44.443 --> 00:00:45.645
<i> by setting
 themselves on fire.</i>

00:00:47.447 --> 00:00:49.482
<i> Many, many women were
 dying in child birth.</i>

00:00:51.083 --> 00:00:53.486
<i> I was kidnapped
 by Gaddafi's troops.</i>

00:00:55.421 --> 00:00:56.890
<i> There was no place to hide.</i>

00:00:59.125 --> 00:01:00.794
(applause)

00:01:05.799 --> 00:01:10.369 line:0%
So I was 26 the first time
I went to Afghanistan.

00:01:10.436 --> 00:01:13.005 line:0%
And I had been
living in India at the time.

00:01:13.072 --> 00:01:16.208
And I had a roommate
who went to Afghanistan

00:01:16.275 --> 00:01:17.710
under the Taliban
and he came back

00:01:17.777 --> 00:01:20.013
and he said, "You know,
you are a woman.

00:01:20.079 --> 00:01:21.347
You should go to Afghanistan

00:01:21.414 --> 00:01:23.282
and photograph women living
under the Taliban,

00:01:23.348 --> 00:01:24.918
because no one's doing it."

00:01:24.984 --> 00:01:26.819
And he didn't tell me

00:01:26.886 --> 00:01:29.022
that photography
was illegal at the time,

00:01:29.089 --> 00:01:32.391
that you couldn't photograph
any living thing.

00:01:32.458 --> 00:01:34.326
And that there was
no American Embassy,

00:01:34.393 --> 00:01:37.063
and that the only
governing body was the Taliban,

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:40.499
which was
ruled by Sharia law.

00:01:40.566 --> 00:01:44.770
But I was 26 and I didn't care,
and so, I went.

00:01:44.837 --> 00:01:47.240
And I took
some pictures of women.

00:01:47.306 --> 00:01:48.707
I kept my cameras in my bag,

00:01:48.774 --> 00:01:50.843
and I ran around
to people's homes.

00:01:50.910 --> 00:01:52.478
And I went
to the hospitals--

00:01:52.544 --> 00:01:55.415
this was
a women's hospital in 2000.

00:01:55.481 --> 00:01:59.118
There was no medicine,
very few doctors.

00:01:59.185 --> 00:02:00.553
This was a woman in labor.

00:02:02.989 --> 00:02:06.091
This is a very typical scene
on the streets of Kabul.

00:02:06.158 --> 00:02:08.227
This was the capital
at the time.

00:02:08.294 --> 00:02:10.263
There were almost no cars.

00:02:10.329 --> 00:02:12.531
Women beggars were
really the only women

00:02:12.598 --> 00:02:14.366
you would
ever see on the street.

00:02:14.433 --> 00:02:17.804
Any form of entertainment
was illegal.

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:21.007
There was no music,
no television,

00:02:21.074 --> 00:02:22.541
and no cell phone.

00:02:22.608 --> 00:02:24.510
So, when I would go to
Afghanistan at the time,

00:02:24.577 --> 00:02:26.712
I would literally fall off
the face of the planet.

00:02:26.779 --> 00:02:29.215
I would have no idea
what was happening

00:02:29.281 --> 00:02:30.884
outside of Afghanistan.

00:02:32.085 --> 00:02:35.854
This scene happened.
I was out at a refugee camp

00:02:35.921 --> 00:02:37.523
because there was
a drought in Herat,

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:39.125
which was
western Afghanistan.

00:02:39.191 --> 00:02:41.327
And I was with my driver
and he said,

00:02:41.393 --> 00:02:42.795
"Madam, I have to go early,

00:02:42.862 --> 00:02:44.430
because my brother
is getting married."

00:02:44.497 --> 00:02:45.498
And I said, "Great.

00:02:45.564 --> 00:02:48.067
Let's go to your
brother's wedding."

00:02:48.134 --> 00:02:50.035
So, he took me in.

00:02:50.102 --> 00:02:53.272
I brought one camera,
one lens and I hung out.

00:02:53.339 --> 00:02:55.942
And I had been on a street,
like the picture

00:02:56.009 --> 00:02:57.042
you had just seen.

00:02:57.109 --> 00:02:59.111
And we descended
down these stairs

00:02:59.178 --> 00:03:01.681
and the Titanic
was blasting.

00:03:01.747 --> 00:03:03.682
And men and women
were dancing together.

00:03:03.749 --> 00:03:06.085
And this was all under
the Taliban in secret.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:10.656
About 9 years later,
National Geographic

00:03:10.723 --> 00:03:12.992
assigned me to photograph
women in Afghanistan.

00:03:13.058 --> 00:03:15.527
And I spent about 2 years
photographing.

00:03:15.594 --> 00:03:18.031
And the changes
that had been made

00:03:18.097 --> 00:03:19.132
were astonishing to me.

00:03:19.198 --> 00:03:21.734
I had been working
pretty much consistently

00:03:21.801 --> 00:03:25.071
in Afghanistan since 2000,
so I went almost every year.

00:03:25.138 --> 00:03:30.376
And my last trip
was about 5 months ago.

00:03:30.443 --> 00:03:32.812
This is a wedding.

00:03:32.879 --> 00:03:35.047
The man on the right
is the father of the groom

00:03:35.114 --> 00:03:38.150
and he is a filmmaker
in Afghanistan.

00:03:38.217 --> 00:03:40.519
This is a typical scene
of a midwife.

00:03:40.586 --> 00:03:42.788
This is
in Badakhshan Province.

00:03:42.855 --> 00:03:44.991
And that province
has very few roads.

00:03:45.058 --> 00:03:48.561
So, many, many women die
in childbirth in Afghanistan,

00:03:48.627 --> 00:03:51.030
mostly because of the
lack of access to hospitals

00:03:51.097 --> 00:03:52.231
and doctors.

00:03:52.298 --> 00:03:54.800
So, what you see
here is a woman,

00:03:54.867 --> 00:03:58.504
a midwife from Merlin,
and she would go out

00:03:58.571 --> 00:04:00.006
into very remote villages

00:04:00.072 --> 00:04:01.907
and they would make
an announcement at the mosque.

00:04:01.974 --> 00:04:04.543
And pregnant women
and women with young children

00:04:04.610 --> 00:04:07.379
would come
and meet with her.

00:04:07.446 --> 00:04:08.781
And after spending
about two weeks

00:04:08.848 --> 00:04:11.684
in Badakhshan Province,
I was driving back to Fayzabad,

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:13.286
which is the capital.

00:04:13.352 --> 00:04:16.021
And I notice these two women
on the side of the mountain.

00:04:16.088 --> 00:04:17.356
And I said,
"That's strange,

00:04:17.423 --> 00:04:19.091
there's no man
with those women."

00:04:19.158 --> 00:04:22.128
And anyone who's worked
extensively in Afghanistan

00:04:22.194 --> 00:04:24.897
knows that there was always
a man with the women.

00:04:24.964 --> 00:04:27.567
So we stop the car
and Dr. Zieba,

00:04:27.633 --> 00:04:30.837
who was my translator
and an amazing Afghan woman,

00:04:30.903 --> 00:04:33.072
she jumped out
and we ran up the mountain

00:04:33.139 --> 00:04:34.474
and she said,
"What's going on?"

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:37.009
And the woman
on the right was in labor,

00:04:37.076 --> 00:04:39.378
and her water
had just broken.

00:04:39.445 --> 00:04:43.082
And they had rented a car
and her husband's first wife

00:04:43.148 --> 00:04:44.383
had died in childbirth.

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:47.420
And he was so determined
to not have a second wife die

00:04:47.487 --> 00:04:49.221
in childbirth
that he rented this car,

00:04:49.288 --> 00:04:51.824
and they were driving
from their village to Fayzabad,

00:04:51.891 --> 00:04:53.859
the capital,
and their car broke down.

00:04:53.926 --> 00:04:55.561
And so I said, "Get in my car

00:04:55.628 --> 00:04:57.162
and I'll take you
to the hospital."

00:04:57.229 --> 00:04:58.297
And they said, "We can't.

00:04:58.364 --> 00:05:00.132
We need the permission
of her husband."

00:05:00.199 --> 00:05:02.502
And so I said, "Dr. Zieba,
go find the husband."

00:05:02.568 --> 00:05:03.936
And fortunately
there was a one road

00:05:04.002 --> 00:05:05.605
that led throughout
the whole province.

00:05:05.671 --> 00:05:07.740
So, she took our car
and she found

00:05:07.806 --> 00:05:10.109
the husband.
They all came in my car,

00:05:10.176 --> 00:05:11.177
and she delivered.

00:05:11.243 --> 00:05:13.078
Everyone always
asks me if I took--

00:05:13.145 --> 00:05:15.248
if I have
pictures of her delivering.

00:05:15.314 --> 00:05:17.482
And I stopped
photographing at the point

00:05:17.549 --> 00:05:20.119
that I left them,
that I put them in my car,

00:05:20.186 --> 00:05:22.087
because I changed the story
as a journalist

00:05:22.154 --> 00:05:23.589
and I didn't feel like it
was ethical

00:05:23.655 --> 00:05:25.825
to keep photographing.

00:05:25.891 --> 00:05:28.126
Many women in Afghanistan
end up in prison

00:05:28.193 --> 00:05:32.999
simply for asking for a divorce,
for doing things

00:05:33.066 --> 00:05:35.134
that in the west,
we would see

00:05:35.201 --> 00:05:37.903
as not justifiable
to end up in prison.

00:05:37.970 --> 00:05:39.905
This is Mida Hall.
She was married

00:05:39.972 --> 00:05:41.907
at a very young age to a man
who was decades

00:05:41.974 --> 00:05:43.042
older than her.

00:05:43.109 --> 00:05:46.679
He was handicapped,
so every day her duties

00:05:46.745 --> 00:05:50.082
as a wife were to bathe him
and to take care of him

00:05:50.149 --> 00:05:51.283
and feed him.

00:05:51.350 --> 00:05:54.987
When she was 21,
she asked for a divorce

00:05:55.054 --> 00:05:57.490
and she was thrown in prison
by his brothers.

00:05:59.225 --> 00:06:00.760
This is a young woman.

00:06:00.826 --> 00:06:03.762
Women in Afghanistan
who are unhappy

00:06:03.829 --> 00:06:07.266
or who are ashamed,
they don't take a gun

00:06:07.333 --> 00:06:09.869
and try and commit suicide
the way that we would try to

00:06:09.935 --> 00:06:12.371
or that's more typical
in the west.

00:06:12.438 --> 00:06:13.872
They set themselves
on fire.

00:06:13.939 --> 00:06:16.775
And many of those
women don't die.

00:06:16.842 --> 00:06:19.411
So, I did a series
for<i> The New York Times</i>

00:06:19.478 --> 00:06:21.013
on women who tried
to commit suicide

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:22.814
by setting themselves
on fire.

00:06:22.881 --> 00:06:24.550
This young woman
had been accused

00:06:24.617 --> 00:06:27.753
by her neighbors of stealing.
And she was so ashamed

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:29.188
that she tried
to kill herself.

00:06:29.255 --> 00:06:31.290
And she died a few days
after that picture.

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:36.461
With the Americans
in Afghanistan,

00:06:36.528 --> 00:06:38.364
one thing they tried
to do was train up

00:06:38.430 --> 00:06:39.998
a police force of women.

00:06:40.065 --> 00:06:43.136
And this is at a shooting range
outside of Kabul.

00:06:44.703 --> 00:06:47.506
Education has really
picked up in Kabul,

00:06:47.506 --> 00:06:49.174
that's something
when I first I used to go,

00:06:49.241 --> 00:06:52.245
there were secret girl schools
in people's homes,

00:06:52.311 --> 00:06:53.712
hidden from the Taliban.

00:06:53.779 --> 00:06:55.714
And now you see
women graduating.

00:06:55.781 --> 00:06:57.884
This is a women's
boxing team.

00:06:59.685 --> 00:07:02.388
This is a woman
in parliament.

00:07:04.423 --> 00:07:06.025
They're women in parliament,
sorry.

00:07:06.091 --> 00:07:10.095
There are soap operas with women
and women actresses.

00:07:10.162 --> 00:07:13.499
This is a soap opera set,
in Kabul.

00:07:13.566 --> 00:07:15.368
This is Trina.
She is an actress.

00:07:15.434 --> 00:07:18.404
She did soap operas
and she was also in some movies.

00:07:18.471 --> 00:07:23.810
So, in 2009 and 2010,
I accompanied the Marines'

00:07:23.876 --> 00:07:26.645
female engagement teams,
throughout Helmand Province.

00:07:26.712 --> 00:07:29.114
This was a program,
started by the Marines,

00:07:29.181 --> 00:07:32.150
to have American women
engage Afghan women,

00:07:32.217 --> 00:07:33.719
because
many of the Marines--

00:07:33.785 --> 00:07:37.056
all the Marines operating
in Helmand Province were men.

00:07:37.123 --> 00:07:39.291
And there was
a whole 50% of the society,

00:07:39.358 --> 00:07:42.161
they couldn't--
they couldn't engage.

00:07:42.227 --> 00:07:43.895
And they couldn't go
into people's homes.

00:07:43.962 --> 00:07:47.767
So, they brought women in.
And they had them

00:07:47.833 --> 00:07:49.835
talk to Afghan women,
look at them

00:07:49.901 --> 00:07:52.371
for basic medical treatment.

00:07:52.438 --> 00:07:53.906
It was
fascinating for me,

00:07:53.973 --> 00:07:55.875
because I had been
embedding with the military

00:07:55.942 --> 00:07:59.544
for many, many years,
but I was always the only woman.

00:07:59.611 --> 00:08:00.813
So, it was the first time

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:02.615
that I was able to be
around women,

00:08:02.681 --> 00:08:05.951
to go around and see
how they operate

00:08:06.017 --> 00:08:07.820
in this hostile environment.

00:08:09.955 --> 00:08:12.324
This is a female
Blackhawk Pilot, Jesse.

00:08:12.391 --> 00:08:14.426
And she used to go in
and pick up the injured.

00:08:14.493 --> 00:08:16.062
She was working
with the Medevac Team.

00:08:17.663 --> 00:08:20.465
This is them, training.

00:08:20.532 --> 00:08:23.135
This is
all in Helmand Province:

00:08:23.202 --> 00:08:25.004
cleaning their guns,

00:08:25.071 --> 00:08:26.705
relaxing at night.

00:08:26.772 --> 00:08:28.007
And it was the first time--
You know,

00:08:28.007 --> 00:08:29.574
usually when I embed
with the military,

00:08:29.641 --> 00:08:31.376
there's no place
for me to sleep.

00:08:31.443 --> 00:08:32.978
It's always
this big crisis,

00:08:33.045 --> 00:08:36.148
where is the female journalist
gonna sleep.

00:08:36.215 --> 00:08:38.017
And so, I finally
was able to sleep

00:08:38.084 --> 00:08:40.186
in a normal cot
with a bunch of women,

00:08:40.252 --> 00:08:42.821
which was really fun.

00:08:42.888 --> 00:08:45.457
And I loved seeing them
still try and do their makeup

00:08:45.524 --> 00:08:48.427
and be feminine
even on the front lines.

00:08:48.494 --> 00:08:49.995
And we patrolled.

00:08:50.062 --> 00:08:51.097
And we were shot at.

00:08:51.163 --> 00:08:53.699
This was before 2013,

00:08:53.765 --> 00:08:57.536
when women were allowed
on the frontlines.

00:08:57.602 --> 00:09:00.739
So, this is all in 2010.

00:09:00.806 --> 00:09:03.208
(audience laughing)

00:09:03.275 --> 00:09:04.677
I love this picture.

00:09:06.545 --> 00:09:10.416
In 2009, I was given
a MacArthur Fellowship

00:09:10.483 --> 00:09:13.352
and I wanted to focus on
maternal mortality,

00:09:13.419 --> 00:09:15.588
and why women die
in childbirth.

00:09:15.654 --> 00:09:17.189
And so--

00:09:17.256 --> 00:09:19.125
And it's a body of work
that I have been doing

00:09:19.191 --> 00:09:20.959
now for about 5 years.

00:09:21.026 --> 00:09:23.896
I went to Sierra Leone,
to photograph

00:09:23.962 --> 00:09:26.031
in the Magburaka
government hospital.

00:09:26.097 --> 00:09:28.467
It was a place that I knew
many, many women

00:09:28.534 --> 00:09:29.701
were dying in childbirth.

00:09:29.768 --> 00:09:33.005
I went there one day
and met Mama Sise.

00:09:33.072 --> 00:09:35.507
She was a woman
who was pregnant with twins.

00:09:35.574 --> 00:09:38.076
She gave birth to the first twin
in the village,

00:09:38.143 --> 00:09:40.312
and the second twin
wouldn't come out.

00:09:40.379 --> 00:09:43.015
So, she took
a canoe across the river.

00:09:43.082 --> 00:09:44.516
There was
an ambulance waiting

00:09:44.583 --> 00:09:45.817
for her across the river.

00:09:45.884 --> 00:09:48.587
And she drove about
4 hours, across bumpy roads,

00:09:48.653 --> 00:09:49.821
to get to the hospital.

00:09:49.821 --> 00:09:51.690
And this is when I met her.

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:54.493
She had delivered the first baby
about 24 hours earlier.

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:57.095
She was so scared
and tired to push,

00:09:57.162 --> 00:10:00.365
because she was
just exhausted.

00:10:00.432 --> 00:10:02.935
And she finally gave birth
and the baby was--

00:10:03.002 --> 00:10:05.937
I thought, was still born.
But the nurses spent about

00:10:06.004 --> 00:10:08.207
45 minutes
resuscitating the baby.

00:10:09.942 --> 00:10:11.510
And they have
very little there.

00:10:11.576 --> 00:10:13.011
They don't have
traditional machines

00:10:13.078 --> 00:10:15.781
like we do that can--
oxygen and everything.

00:10:15.848 --> 00:10:17.683
They're literally
smacking the baby

00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:20.252
and trying to bring the baby
back to life.

00:10:20.318 --> 00:10:23.589
In that time, Mama Sise
started bleeding.

00:10:23.655 --> 00:10:24.957
I thought there was
something wrong,

00:10:25.023 --> 00:10:27.326
but I'm not a doctor,
I'm just a photo-journalist.

00:10:27.393 --> 00:10:29.761
And so I kept asking,
"Why is she bleeding so much?"

00:10:29.828 --> 00:10:31.831
And they were just
mopping up the blood

00:10:31.897 --> 00:10:33.966
and saying she's fine.

00:10:34.033 --> 00:10:35.468
Finally, I went
to go get the doctor,

00:10:35.534 --> 00:10:36.669
and he was in surgery.

00:10:36.736 --> 00:10:39.104
When I came back,
her blood pressure was down

00:10:39.171 --> 00:10:41.240
to 60 over 40.

00:10:41.306 --> 00:10:43.676
They picked her up
and carried her across

00:10:43.742 --> 00:10:45.444
the hospital
where the doctor was.

00:10:45.511 --> 00:10:47.980
There was one doctor
in the entire province.

00:10:49.314 --> 00:10:52.418
And by the time
she got there, she died.

00:10:53.952 --> 00:10:56.055
This is her sister
who was also a midwife,

00:10:56.121 --> 00:10:58.324
who had arranged
to send her that ambulance

00:10:58.390 --> 00:10:59.992
because
she didn't want her to die.

00:11:01.427 --> 00:11:03.662
This is the mother finding out
that her daughter

00:11:03.729 --> 00:11:05.965
has just died.

00:11:06.065 --> 00:11:09.301
And this is in the ambulance.
I went home with her body...

00:11:10.702 --> 00:11:12.037
and photographed the rituals

00:11:12.103 --> 00:11:14.439
surrounding her death

00:11:14.506 --> 00:11:16.408
and her burial.

00:11:16.475 --> 00:11:18.911
So, two years later
I got a call from Doctors

00:11:18.977 --> 00:11:20.378
Without Borders, MSF.

00:11:20.478 --> 00:11:22.848
And they said, "We saw
the story you did.

00:11:22.882 --> 00:11:26.618
And since then we've put
five ambulances in Bo province,"

00:11:26.685 --> 00:11:28.721
in this one province
next to that province

00:11:28.788 --> 00:11:30.022
I'd been in.

00:11:30.088 --> 00:11:33.024
And they offer 24 hour
emergency service

00:11:33.091 --> 00:11:35.294
to women in Sierra Leone,
in that province,

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:37.463
and they gave
each of the small clinics

00:11:37.529 --> 00:11:39.064
in the villages a radio.

00:11:39.130 --> 00:11:41.166
So, when a woman
went into the clinic

00:11:41.233 --> 00:11:42.901
with complications,

00:11:42.968 --> 00:11:44.470
they could call
for an ambulance.

00:11:44.536 --> 00:11:46.205
And they said, "With that,
we've reduced

00:11:46.271 --> 00:11:49.642
the maternal mortality rate
by 60%."

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:53.379
( indistinct chattering )

00:12:21.106 --> 00:12:24.009
( indistinct chattering
continues )

00:13:38.083 --> 00:13:41.453 line:0%
( speaking
