00:17:37.156 --> 00:17:41.393
In 2011--
It was February of 2011,

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:45.063
and I had watched
the Arab Spring unfold from--

00:17:45.129 --> 00:17:47.565
On TV
while I was sitting in Iraq.

00:17:47.632 --> 00:17:49.734
And when I was in Afghanistan,

00:17:49.801 --> 00:17:53.238
and then, Bahrain.
I was always in the wrong place.

00:17:53.238 --> 00:17:55.040
So, I called
<i> The New York Times</i>

00:17:55.106 --> 00:17:57.075
and I said,
"I am going to Libya,

00:17:57.141 --> 00:17:58.977
whether you want
to send me or not."

00:17:59.044 --> 00:18:01.346
So, I went to Libya.

00:18:01.413 --> 00:18:04.616
Like most journalists,
I crossed illegally

00:18:04.683 --> 00:18:07.619
from Egypt into Eastern Libya.

00:18:07.686 --> 00:18:10.055
That was really
the only way to do it,

00:18:10.122 --> 00:18:12.457
because any journalist
who wants to cover an uprising,

00:18:12.523 --> 00:18:13.492
the government generally

00:18:13.559 --> 00:18:14.926
doesn't want
journalists there.

00:18:14.993 --> 00:18:16.728
So, you have to sneak in.

00:18:16.794 --> 00:18:19.864
When I got there,
it was very euphoric.

00:18:19.931 --> 00:18:22.668
People were really celebrating
the uprising.

00:18:22.734 --> 00:18:25.770
A parallel government
was being set up.

00:18:25.837 --> 00:18:29.874
There were demonstrations.
People were really happy.

00:18:29.941 --> 00:18:32.911
They thought Gaddafi
was gonna fall quickly.

00:18:32.978 --> 00:18:35.013
They called people
to fight against

00:18:35.080 --> 00:18:39.084
Gaddafi's troops,
and they were clearly untrained.

00:18:39.151 --> 00:18:41.085
There were doctors,
engineers,

00:18:41.152 --> 00:18:44.123
teachers, learning
how to use weapons.

00:18:45.991 --> 00:18:47.659
Immigrants were fleeing.

00:18:47.726 --> 00:18:50.361
People who had gone to
Libya to work, were trying

00:18:50.428 --> 00:18:51.997
to get boats out
of the country.

00:18:52.064 --> 00:18:54.032
They felt that the fighting
was imminent.

00:18:54.099 --> 00:18:58.670
And in Benghazi,
there was really an
air of tension.

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:00.239
About a week
after I got there,

00:19:00.305 --> 00:19:02.174
some rebels started
pushing forward

00:19:02.240 --> 00:19:04.042
towards the front line.

00:19:04.109 --> 00:19:05.810
And a handful
of photographers--

00:19:05.877 --> 00:19:09.280
It's always the
crazy photographers
who go forward.

00:19:09.347 --> 00:19:12.717
We started moving forward
with Gaddafi's troops.

00:19:12.784 --> 00:19:14.686
We ended up
on the front line.

00:19:14.753 --> 00:19:16.221
This is Ra's Lanuf.

00:19:16.287 --> 00:19:19.090
What you see in the background
is an oil refinery.

00:19:19.157 --> 00:19:21.426
And we followed them,
as cities fell

00:19:21.493 --> 00:19:23.729
from Gaddafi's hands
into rebel hands.

00:19:23.795 --> 00:19:25.530
They went in,
they would shoot out

00:19:25.596 --> 00:19:27.900
pictures of Gaddafi,
go into homes.

00:19:29.334 --> 00:19:31.236
The fighting was really
disproportionate.

00:19:31.303 --> 00:19:35.106
Gaddafi had a trained military,
and we were with the rebels.

00:19:35.173 --> 00:19:38.676
So, this is an example of --
We were on the front line.

00:19:38.743 --> 00:19:41.146
It was one road
that sliced through the desert,

00:19:41.213 --> 00:19:42.513
from west to east.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:44.783
One day,
we were on the front line

00:19:44.849 --> 00:19:47.152
when a helicopter gunship
came in directly

00:19:47.218 --> 00:19:49.454
above us and started spraying
the ground around us with

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:52.290
.50 caliber bullets,
like this big.

00:19:52.356 --> 00:19:55.927
They had to fight back
with Kalashnikovs.

00:19:55.993 --> 00:19:57.929
Some of the soldiers--
Some of the rebels

00:19:57.996 --> 00:20:00.299
were throwing
rocks up into the air.

00:20:01.132 --> 00:20:02.734
Many times,
they just turned around

00:20:02.801 --> 00:20:05.904
and fled when Gaddafi's
military approached.

00:20:05.970 --> 00:20:08.373
We had been
sort of spoiled by being

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:11.076
with the American military,
the Marines in Afghanistan

00:20:11.143 --> 00:20:13.611
and Iraq.
And it was very different.

00:20:13.678 --> 00:20:15.880
This particular day,
we were being pummeled

00:20:15.947 --> 00:20:17.916
with tank fire, mortar rounds.

00:20:17.983 --> 00:20:19.584
We would just
follow the front line,

00:20:19.651 --> 00:20:21.219
as it pushed back
and forward.

00:20:21.286 --> 00:20:23.588
We were really trying to get
a sense of what was happening.

00:20:23.654 --> 00:20:26.557
And it was before
the no-fly zone was
put in place.

00:20:26.557 --> 00:20:28.593
So, as journalists,
we really wanted to show

00:20:28.659 --> 00:20:30.528
what was happening so that--

00:20:30.595 --> 00:20:34.266
While the no-fly zone
was being deliberated,

00:20:34.332 --> 00:20:36.201
we can provide
a firsthand picture

00:20:36.268 --> 00:20:37.936
of what was happening
on the ground.

00:20:39.804 --> 00:20:41.473
The rebels were
really getting injured

00:20:41.539 --> 00:20:43.175
and killed around us.

00:20:43.241 --> 00:20:45.744
The fighting was
very, very intense.

00:20:45.810 --> 00:20:47.246
There was no place to hide.

00:20:48.847 --> 00:20:51.082
We would be on the front line
and we would hear

00:20:51.149 --> 00:20:53.618
the hum of an aircraft.
And you would literally

00:20:53.685 --> 00:20:56.854
just hope that the bomb
didn't land on top of you.

00:20:56.921 --> 00:20:58.323
Cower in fear.

00:20:58.390 --> 00:21:01.192
This particular bomb
landed about 100, 200 feet

00:21:01.259 --> 00:21:03.295
from where we were
standing.

00:21:03.361 --> 00:21:07.299
And we pushed forward with them,
as they took more ground.

00:21:07.399 --> 00:21:09.600
Several days
after that I took this picture,

00:21:09.667 --> 00:21:11.436
I was kidnapped by
Gaddafi's troops

00:21:11.503 --> 00:21:14.072
with three other journalists
for<i> The New York Times.</i>

00:21:15.207 --> 00:21:16.942
So, that was the last picture
in that series.

00:21:18.576 --> 00:21:21.213
Luckily, I had a premonition
that something might happen,

00:21:21.279 --> 00:21:23.849
so I sent a hard drive out
with a colleague

00:21:23.915 --> 00:21:26.284
and said,
"if I get taken,

00:21:26.351 --> 00:21:28.019
please send this
to my agency."

00:21:28.086 --> 00:21:30.889
And that's how I was able
to salvage all my pictures.

00:21:30.955 --> 00:21:34.192
Last year, I wanted to cover
what was happening in Syria.

00:21:34.259 --> 00:21:37.962
But my family begged me
not to go into Syria.

00:21:38.029 --> 00:21:40.298
So, I started covering
the refugee crisis.

00:21:40.365 --> 00:21:44.135
I've made eight trips
to the region: Turkey,

00:21:44.202 --> 00:21:47.138
Jordan, Lebanon,
Northern Iraq,

00:21:47.205 --> 00:21:48.840
and I did go
once into Syria.

00:21:50.575 --> 00:21:52.243
And so, this is
a collection of photos

00:21:52.310 --> 00:21:54.312
with the Syrian refugees.

00:21:54.379 --> 00:21:57.282
These are refugees streaming
into Northern Iraq.

00:21:59.417 --> 00:22:01.219
And this is them
waiting for handouts

00:22:01.286 --> 00:22:03.388
in Northern Iraq,
after arriving.

00:22:03.454 --> 00:22:05.489
This is a food distribution
in Zaatari,

00:22:05.556 --> 00:22:08.460
when there were
riots for bread.

00:22:08.526 --> 00:22:10.561
This is a family
arriving in Zaatari

00:22:10.628 --> 00:22:12.731
for the first time,

00:22:12.797 --> 00:22:14.532
and when they're getting

00:22:14.599 --> 00:22:17.969
registered with the
United Nations, in Zaatari.

00:22:18.036 --> 00:22:21.606
And a family sleeping outside,
at dawn, in Iraq.

00:22:23.542 --> 00:22:26.544
This is a funeral
for a rebel fighter.

00:22:26.611 --> 00:22:27.579
And they're cooking.

00:22:27.846 --> 00:22:30.449
The body was still in Syria,
but this is the family cooking.

00:22:31.983 --> 00:22:34.419
People were
living in caves, in Lebanon.

00:22:34.486 --> 00:22:37.422
I went back to these caves
several months ago,

00:22:37.489 --> 00:22:40.758
and the families have all been
moved into makeshift camps.

00:22:40.825 --> 00:22:42.127
There are no camps in Lebanon,

00:22:42.193 --> 00:22:43.962
because
the Lebanese government is--

00:22:44.028 --> 00:22:46.965
Does not want
formal camps set up.

00:22:47.032 --> 00:22:49.167
This is at a bread distribution,
in Zaatari.

00:22:50.101 --> 00:22:52.537
And these are the camps on the
Syrian side of the border.

00:22:52.603 --> 00:22:54.572
People were
living in raw sewage.

00:22:54.639 --> 00:22:57.775
There were no NGOs
working there except IHH,

00:22:57.842 --> 00:23:00.145
a Turkish NGO at the time.

00:23:00.211 --> 00:23:02.147
And this is in Syria.

00:23:02.214 --> 00:23:05.516
He was a former fighter
and he was living in a school

00:23:05.583 --> 00:23:06.951
with his family.

00:23:07.018 --> 00:23:10.755
This is outside of
a smuggler's village in Turkey.

00:23:10.821 --> 00:23:13.124
I was waiting to try
and photograph

00:23:13.191 --> 00:23:16.094
the exodus of refugees
coming out of Syria.

00:23:16.161 --> 00:23:18.196
And it's a picture
that's very, very difficult

00:23:18.263 --> 00:23:19.597
to get as a photographer now,

00:23:19.664 --> 00:23:21.566
because all of the neighboring
countries have really

00:23:21.632 --> 00:23:23.134
shut down their borders.

00:23:23.201 --> 00:23:26.637
So, I stood outside
of the smuggler's village,

00:23:26.704 --> 00:23:28.572
because I knew
that they were crossing there.

00:23:28.639 --> 00:23:30.708
And every hour or so,
someone would come up

00:23:30.775 --> 00:23:31.710
to me and say,
"Get out of here,

00:23:31.776 --> 00:23:32.743
we're gonna kill you."

00:23:32.810 --> 00:23:34.545
And one guy came up
to me and he said,

00:23:34.612 --> 00:23:36.481
"I'm gonna
go get my knife."

00:23:36.547 --> 00:23:37.915
Another guy
came up to me and said,

00:23:37.982 --> 00:23:40.518
"Just wait until dark,
because when dark comes,

00:23:40.585 --> 00:23:41.919
you'll see all the refugees."

00:23:41.986 --> 00:23:44.189
So, I put my cameras in my bag
and I waited.

00:23:44.256 --> 00:23:46.992
And, of course, at dark
they all started streaming out.

00:23:48.093 --> 00:23:51.563
This is
a family living in a camp

00:23:51.630 --> 00:23:53.731
across from a formal camp,
in Turkey.

00:23:53.798 --> 00:23:56.367
They were literally
living under the trees.

00:23:56.434 --> 00:23:57.836
And this is
that same camp.

00:23:59.370 --> 00:24:01.740
I just want to show you
a few on-assignment pictures,

00:24:01.806 --> 00:24:03.941
because I think it's funny.

00:24:04.008 --> 00:24:07.345
This was me in 2001,
in Pakistan.

00:24:07.411 --> 00:24:09.914
This is me,
in Fallujah.

00:24:09.981 --> 00:24:13.952
Crossing illegally into Darfur,
to cover the war in Darfur.

00:24:14.052 --> 00:24:15.987
We had to walk
for three kilometers,

00:24:16.053 --> 00:24:17.622
most of that through wadis.

00:24:19.224 --> 00:24:20.458
This is--

00:24:20.525 --> 00:24:22.360
We had lived on the
back of this pickup truck

00:24:22.427 --> 00:24:26.064
for five days, driving through
the desert in Darfur.

00:24:26.131 --> 00:24:28.632
This is the Korangal Valley,
in Afghanistan.

00:24:28.699 --> 00:24:30.735
I was embedded
with the 173rd.

00:24:30.802 --> 00:24:34.138
That's me and my colleague,
in Afghanistan.

00:24:34.205 --> 00:24:36.274
That's me
and that same colleague.

00:24:36.341 --> 00:24:38.275
( laughter )

00:24:38.776 --> 00:24:41.278
Sort of like
being an actor.

00:24:41.345 --> 00:24:43.715
And this is us hiding
in that silo, in Libya,

00:24:43.782 --> 00:24:44.983
on the front line.

00:24:46.251 --> 00:24:48.219
And this is us
on the front line.

00:24:48.285 --> 00:24:50.088
That's me with Tyler Hicks.

00:24:50.154 --> 00:24:51.322
And we were taken together.

00:24:51.389 --> 00:24:53.592
That's Gary Cosgrove
and Nikki Sobecki.

00:24:54.726 --> 00:24:58.462
And this is an example of
where we stay typically,

00:24:58.562 --> 00:25:00.097
in Libya, on the front line.

00:25:00.164 --> 00:25:02.566
People-- Libyans would
just open their homes

00:25:02.633 --> 00:25:04.235
to journalists
who were there.

00:25:04.301 --> 00:25:06.304
And for example,
in this particular house,

00:25:06.371 --> 00:25:08.472
there were
17 journalists sleeping.

00:25:08.539 --> 00:25:10.408
And every night ,
we got a knock on the door

00:25:10.475 --> 00:25:13.712
at about 6:00, and it was
a 10-year-old Libyan boy.

00:25:13.778 --> 00:25:15.613
He would come
with a giant tray of food

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:17.315
and just set it down and leave.

00:25:17.382 --> 00:25:19.684
And so, the women who were
still in the village would

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:21.486
cook for us every night.

00:25:21.552 --> 00:25:23.588
And on the upper right
is Anthony Shadid.

00:25:23.655 --> 00:25:26.424
He is a colleague,
and he died in Syria last year

00:25:26.491 --> 00:25:27.926
of an asthma attack.

00:25:29.628 --> 00:25:31.029
And that's it.

00:25:31.096 --> 00:25:32.831
( applause )

